$1.21 price. Stock is selling about 11x it's best year's earnings of the past
five years. Revenue seems to be rangebound between $15-18M per annum. Stock has
often traded at or above $2/sh. That'd be a nice percentage gain from today's
$1.21 if the stock once more trades there ($2.00) or higher again.

Unless I could see a catalyst for TRCI though, for me,I'd rather make new stock
market commitments elsewhere. With the market risk apparently very high
(contining downtrend in stocks), I'd rather be looking to make new purchases in
downtrodden companies where at least the business risk is perceived as
low(because of earnings or sales history, or market share, or patents,
resources, etc.)

In other words, for me, given that I have a finite amount of funds to invest,
I'd rather be looking at a Citicorp now(used here as an example, not a
recommendation), where I'm comfortable (but not assured) that the business will
be intact and possibly grow--- and that if there ever is a market upturn, there
might be a decent chance that the company might participate. Whereas, while
committing funds to TRCI @1.21 offers support from the balance sheet, it's more
iffy to me that TRCI would participate in an up market. OTOH, if it did, I'd
guess the percentage rise in TRCI might surpass the percentage rise in a
Citicorp.

