Date:7/14/2002 11:31:25 PM
From:TimbaBear
Hi Paul!

I'm not sure what formula of Graham you are using, but my NetNet formula IS
almost purely Graham's method of discounting the various asset classes by
various percentages, totaling the results, subtracting 100% of the liabilities
and then dividing the answer by the number of shares. The only "liberties" I
take with his methodology are that I don't count real estate at 50% if it is
already greatly depreciated(especially in the current real estate environment)
and I don't break out inventories into raw, in-process and finished, but
rather, take the whole inventory and discount it by 1/3.

You would like to see a catalyst for TRCI? How about the increase in military
budgeting and the fact that they used to be entirely dependent on military
contracts and now have 35% of their revenue stream still coming from there? Or
possibly the real estate building boom that is occurring when they supply the
GFI circuit-breakers that have become mandatory in so many building codes?

Regardless of whether either of these or something else is a catalyst or isn't,
the purpose of value investing for me is to buy cash flow cheaply. I get
.37/share cash flow versus my entry price of 1.27. That means they are
producing 29% of increased real value for my investment dollar. Sooner or later
the market will recognize that and price it accordingly. I don't know when or
why, I just believe I bought a nice return on my equity with a substantial
margin of safety from both the NetNet value and the 5% dividend rate.

As far as C is concerned: I haven't done an analysis of C, but when Enron and
WorldCom and Global Crossing and KMart, etc. started going down the tubes with
big debts on the books, I just figure that the biggest US Bank has some
exposure. I don't know how to quantify that exposure partly because they don't
list it by company and partly because I'm not privvy to their underwriting
standards or consistancy of application. I also don't know what exposure they
have to overseas liability or where.

C is just an example of the problem I have with banks, finance companies and
insurance companies. I'm sure that you are far more qualified than I to analyze
these type of companies, so I'll have to take your word for it. I advised a
friend of mine to get out of C in March and he did at about 49. The advice at
that time was based on the cockroach theory as they were being linked in some
way with the Enron blow-up. I forget the particulars now. But, given the
stock's performance since then, he's happy he followed my advice. Could have
just been dumb luck.

Given the way the charts are looking, I don't think I'd be in any hurry to
employ new money in equities right now. It looks to me like bad times mostly
from now through March and maybe into April. But, that's another type of
thread! :~)

I always appreciate your input, Paul. I may not always sound like it, but I do.
Good Luck, and be defensive!

TimbaBear
