Date:7/15/2002 10:13:57 AM
From:Paul Senior
TimbaBear: net-net or net current assets as used by B. Graham is current assets
minus all liabilities (current and long-term).

In my interpretation of how this is used, if an investor uses what I call the
"Jim Clarke approach", where net-nets are carefully further screened for
business prospects or a catalyst, then one would likely also at least consider
off-balance sheet obligations, pension obligations, etc. as liabilities that
are to be subtracted from the current assets figure. Here, one is looking to
buy only a very few "high quality" net-nets.

If one takes the approach that one buys as basket of net-net stocks - if there
even could be such a quantity available today as there was in Dr. Graham's time
- then perhaps Dr. Graham would say the typical investor is likely not to have
the time or inclination to dig out off-balance sheet obligations. And that it
might not be necessary since the basket approach might offset risks that one or
two stocks don't work out because of surprises in off-balance sheet issues.
OTOH, it's my impression that there weren't so many off-balance sheet items in
Dr. Graham's day, so perhaps he might say today to stick with his original
method - find and subtract all these liabilities also.

----------

Quick ratio is quick assets divided by current liabilities. (Where quick assets
are cash, near-cash, and accounts receivable)
%EOM----------------------

%BOM---------------------
Date:7/15/2002 10:47:48 AM
From:Dave
Timba,

This is the criteria for a true "value" stock as proposed by Graham

1. Adequate size (Revenues > 100m)
2. A sufficiently strong financial condition (Current Ratio > 2.0)
3. Continued dividends for at least 20 years.
4. No earnings deficit in the past ten years
5. Ten year growth of at least 33% in EPS (remember this is not annualized)
6. Price of stock no more than 1.5 times net asset value adjusted for
intangibles
7. Price no more than 15 times average EPS of the past three years.

Now, in the book "The Intelligent Investor" in Chapter 15, Graham discusses
what is called "Net Current Asset (or "Bargain") Issues. (See Page 205)

Here is a quote from Page 205 regarding this philosophy.

The idea here was to acquire as many issues as posible at a cost for each of
less than their book value in terms of net-current-assets alone - i.e., giving
no vlaue to the plant account and other assets. Our purchases were made
typically at 2/3s or less of such stripped-down asset value. In most years we
carried a wide divesification here- at least 100 different issues

Now, I believe that in order to do a proper analysis of a companies assets and
liabilities, one would need to read and understand all the footnotes to a
company's financial statements and adjust accordingly. For example, if a
company has sold a portion of their A/R, have they guaranteed any portion of
that A/R? If so, that is a potential liability that should be added. What about
operating leases? That should be added.

Nowadays, I believe analyzing a company as a "value" investment has become
quite complex.
