Date:7/15/2002 7:21:21 PM
From:TimbaBear
Hi Dave!

Do you know of any companies that currently meet all 7 of these criteria?

In my calculation of NetNet value, I use Graham's methodology for discounting
all assets (long and short term). In reading his reasonings, I agreed with his
paradigm of conservative valuation and adopted it as my own.

Many things are different today and many are the same. When he wrote Security
Analysis, the real estate market was also in depression. Additionally, the
value of the real estate and equipment (from what I have been able to gather)
that was carried on the company books was also an inflated value. Today we have
a strong real estate market and real estate seems to be carried at or below
market value and has been depreciated from that value as well. I feel that it
is appropriate to carry PPE valuations for my analysis at his 50% mark, but it
is, to me, more than just taking 1/2 of the number listed for PPE.

Goodwill, on the other hand, seems to me to be rarely worth anything, let alone
50%, so I am quite harsh in my markdowns of that line item.

I agree that analysis is complex today, but I suspect good analysis has always
been so. I have developed a spreadsheet that I use that has 40-50 data fields
and 100 different calculations and manipulations of that data. The process of
reading the 10K's and culling the data is time consuming, so I reserve it for
those stocks that have survived through all of my other, quicker screenings.

I don't believe that I can follow 100 different issues that would comprise a
basket of "bargain issues" so I have tried to adapt Graham's style to my
particular strengths and shortcomings (my wife will confirm that the latter
often seem to outnumber the former). One of those adaptations is the use of
cash flow analysis. I will buy a sufficiently strong cash-flow even it isn't
also a discount price to NetNet.

James Clarke's preference for a dividend opened my eyes to the value added by
that aspect. If I have a decision between several companies, those paying a
dividend will survive the process of elimination (all other things being
similar).

TimbaBear
%EOM----------------------

