%BOM---------------------
Date:7/19/2002 2:07:36 AM
From:Paul Senior
re: "The market has temporarily suspended most links between business
performance and share prices." Maybe so. Maybe not.

The metric I'd use as a link is price (share price) to earnings (business
performance). What seems to be happening is a general lowering of p/e 's across
the board. Certainly I see this with high p/e stocks such as pharmaceuticals,
all of which (that I'm aware of) have had their p/e's cut. While it might be
argued that this is just one sector decline, I'm not aware of any sector that
hasn't had a p/e contraction -- chemicals, industrials, tech... even REITs to
some extent have been affected.

People just don't seem as willing to pay as much for earnings, or maybe it's
earnings growth. What's bothering me is that I could see stock prices coming
down in sectors with lowered earnings (p/e's rising), but I just did not expect
that p/e's overall would be dropping when interest rates are low. I remember
those low under 10 p/e's on Coke, Intel, etc. decades ago, but that was when
bond yields were much, much higher than now and provided an alternative to
stocks. I recently read though where somebody did a study and found that p/e's
can be independent of interest or bond rates. Which might mean that a return to
the low p/e's of decades ago is a possibility in today's low interest rate
environment. That's what seems to be happening, and I'm not liking it.

Paul S.
%EOM----------------------

%BOM---------------------
Date:7/19/2002 2:16:27 AM
From:Dale Baker
I was thinking more in terms of my own portfolio of value small caps. I did a
chart early in July with their trailing PE's and 2002 estimates (these are real
estimates for financial and retail stocks, not software company "hope we close
ten deals on June 30" types) and found them pretty low already.

Then most of those stocks sold off 10-30% this month.

To me, that indicates panic selling by the little guys and fund selling to meet
redemptions. Quality is thrown out along with the junk if the price is going
down, fundamentals be damned.

If I am right, these stocks will have a modest rebound once selling exhaustion
is reached. If you are right, I have a long wait ahead for any substantial
gains.
